1
00:00:00,320 --> 00:00:05,280
The entire SMC industry is built 
on a multi-million dollar lie. 

2
00:00:05,280 --> 00:00:10,240
They took 80-year-old price action 
concepts, gave them new names like  

3
00:00:10,240 --> 00:00:16,640
'order blocks' and 'fair value gaps,' and 
sold them back to you as 'hidden knowledge.' 

4
00:00:16,640 --> 00:00:23,040
In this video, I'm going to prove it. I'll show 
you the original patterns, side-by-side, so you  

5
00:00:23,040 --> 00:00:26,480
never have to pay for this information again.
Market structure 

6
00:00:26,480 --> 00:00:32,320
Market structure stands as one of the purest 
forms of price reading, whether you call it  

7
00:00:32,320 --> 00:00:38,320
price action or smart money concepts.
The core stays the same: price makes  

8
00:00:38,320 --> 00:00:45,680
higher highs and higher lows in uptrends, 
lower highs and lower lows in downtrends. 

9
00:00:45,680 --> 00:00:51,120
In basic price action, you spot a trend 
by connecting these highs and lows. 

10
00:00:51,120 --> 00:00:55,760
A possible trend change happens 
when price breaks this pattern. 

11
00:00:55,760 --> 00:01:00,240
Smart money concepts named this process 
differently, but look at the same  

12
00:01:00,240 --> 00:01:06,800
thing - price breaking its previous rhythm.
 
This chart perfectly shows how price action  

13
00:01:06,800 --> 00:01:12,240
and smart money concepts describe the same 
market behaviors, with different names. 

14
00:01:12,240 --> 00:01:19,200
Price moves up making higher highs and higher 
lows, until a key point where structure breaks. 

15
00:01:19,200 --> 00:01:26,960
In pure price action terms, you spot a trend by 
watching how price climbs in a stair-step pattern. 

16
00:01:26,960 --> 00:01:31,520
Each push up creates a new high, 
followed by a smaller pullback  

17
00:01:31,520 --> 00:01:34,480
that holds above the previous low.
This forms the basic trend structure. 

18
00:01:34,480 --> 00:01:39,520
Notice how in both sides of the 
chart, the pattern looks identical. 

19
00:01:39,520 --> 00:01:43,760
That's because whether you call it 
"trend continuation" or "break of  

20
00:01:43,760 --> 00:01:50,560
structure," the price behavior stays the same. 
 
The market continues moving higher until it hits  

21
00:01:50,560 --> 00:01:55,360
a point where the pattern changes.
Smart money concepts simply gave  

22
00:01:55,360 --> 00:02:01,760
new names to these classic price patterns.
Both methods pay special attention to these  

23
00:02:01,760 --> 00:02:06,640
structure breaks at key levels.
Support and resistance zones  

24
00:02:06,640 --> 00:02:10,400
matter in both approaches.
The market often changes  

25
00:02:10,400 --> 00:02:16,160
direction at these points, showing shifts 
in control between buyers and sellers.
  

26
00:02:17,200 --> 00:02:24,320
Where price action traders see a "trend reversal," 
smart money traders spot a "change of character."  

27
00:02:24,320 --> 00:02:32,160
Both describe that moment when price fails to make 
a new high, and instead breaks below a key level. 

28
00:02:32,160 --> 00:02:37,200
This horizontal line on both sides 
marks this key turning point. 

29
00:02:37,200 --> 00:02:44,960
In price action, this represents a support 
level that, once broken, signals trend reversal. 

30
00:02:44,960 --> 00:02:52,320
Smart money concepts call the same level a "change 
of character", when price shifts direction.
  

31
00:02:52,320 --> 00:02:58,640
Look at how price builds momentum before the 
reversal. It doesn't just flip instantly. 

32
00:02:58,640 --> 00:03:05,360
Instead, it forms a series of pushes higher, 
each one showing less strength than the last. 

33
00:03:05,360 --> 00:03:11,040
This weakness shows up in both trading 
approaches - it's just labeled differently.
  

34
00:03:11,600 --> 00:03:16,240
Also, both methods value 
higher timeframe analysis. 

35
00:03:16,240 --> 00:03:21,520
Structure on larger timeframes gives 
context to smaller timeframe moves. 

36
00:03:21,520 --> 00:03:27,760
So, whether you follow price action or smart money 
concepts, you watch the same price movements,  

37
00:03:27,760 --> 00:03:33,120
you look for the same shifts in market 
behavior, and trade the same opportunities. 

38
00:03:33,120 --> 00:03:33,664
The renaming of these patterns 
didn't change their effectiveness. 
  

39
00:03:33,664 --> 00:03:35,840
Order blocks
Order blocks represent one of  

40
00:03:35,840 --> 00:03:43,120
the clearest examples of how smart money concepts 
simply renamed traditional price action patterns. 

41
00:03:43,120 --> 00:03:48,240
At their core, order blocks mark 
areas where big market players enter  

42
00:03:48,240 --> 00:03:53,520
trades with significant volume.
 
In pure price action analysis,  

43
00:03:53,520 --> 00:03:59,520
traders always watched for strong momentum 
candles that kicked off major moves. 

44
00:03:59,520 --> 00:04:04,720
These candles stood out because they 
showed clear control, either buyers or  

45
00:04:04,720 --> 00:04:10,400
sellers taking charge with conviction.
Smart money concepts just gave these  

46
00:04:10,400 --> 00:04:16,080
candles a fancier name - order blocks.
 
The mechanics stay identical. A bearish  

47
00:04:16,080 --> 00:04:21,600
order block forms when price moves 
up, then reverses down aggressively. 

48
00:04:21,600 --> 00:04:28,640
Price action traders always saw this as a 
supply zone - where sellers overwhelmed buyers. 

49
00:04:28,640 --> 00:04:33,520
The bullish version shows up when 
price drops, then reverses up. 

50
00:04:33,520 --> 00:04:38,000
This is what price action 
traders called demand zones.
  

51
00:04:38,000 --> 00:04:42,560
Smart money concepts added 
specific rules about these zones. 

52
00:04:42,560 --> 00:04:47,760
They say the best order blocks won't 
see price trade past these candle. 

53
00:04:47,760 --> 00:04:54,160
But price action traders noticed this too - 
they just called it a strong reversal level.
  

54
00:04:54,160 --> 00:04:58,480
The market maker angle 
explains why these zones work. 

55
00:04:58,480 --> 00:05:05,440
When big players need to fill large orders, 
they create artificial moves in both directions. 

56
00:05:05,440 --> 00:05:09,520
They open positions at the order 
block level, making it a key  

57
00:05:09,520 --> 00:05:15,680
price zone they'll want to return to later.
This matches perfectly with how price action  

58
00:05:15,680 --> 00:05:22,960
traders always viewed strong reversal candles.
They knew these levels often got retested, because  

59
00:05:22,960 --> 00:05:29,040
they marked important market turning points. 
 
The smart money framework just explains  

60
00:05:29,040 --> 00:05:33,360
why these retests happen.
In fact, you'll often find  

61
00:05:33,360 --> 00:05:40,160
order blocks at major market highs and lows.
This makes sense in both approaches - these  

62
00:05:40,160 --> 00:05:45,440
are the zones where big moves start 
and where trading volume concentrates. 

63
00:05:46,000 --> 00:05:51,760
Price action traders always watched 
these areas for potential reversals.
  

64
00:05:51,760 --> 00:05:57,680
The validity rules stay consistent too.
Both methods watch how price behaves  

65
00:05:57,680 --> 00:06:02,720
when it returns to these zones.
A true order block, like a strong  

66
00:06:02,720 --> 00:06:07,920
support or resistance level, should 
show clear reaction when tested.
  

67
00:06:07,920 --> 00:06:11,920
Market structure plays a 
key role in both approaches. 

68
00:06:11,920 --> 00:06:16,080
Order blocks matter more when 
they break nearby levels. 

69
00:06:16,080 --> 00:06:20,480
SMC traders value a level that 
breaks the market structure. 

70
00:06:20,480 --> 00:06:25,600
At the same time, price action traders 
always gave more weight to reversal  

71
00:06:25,600 --> 00:06:31,840
candles that led to new high or lows.
Both methods recognize that not all  

72
00:06:31,840 --> 00:06:38,480
strong candles become important levels. 
 
The surrounding market context matters most. 

73
00:06:38,480 --> 00:06:44,960
An order block, like any price action pattern, 
needs the right market conditions to work. 

74
00:06:44,960 --> 00:06:49,440
I hope you understand that price 
tells the same story, whether you  

75
00:06:49,440 --> 00:06:56,640
use smart money terms or price action language.
Order blocks simply show where big players entered  

76
00:06:56,640 --> 00:07:04,320
trades. Price action shows strong momentum shifts.
Both describe the same market behavior - just with  

77
00:07:04,320 --> 00:07:06,560
different words.
 
Liquidity sweeps 

78
00:07:06,560 --> 00:07:10,240
Liquidity sweeps form a basic market pattern that  

79
00:07:10,240 --> 00:07:14,080
existed long before smart 
money concepts named them. 

80
00:07:14,080 --> 00:07:20,000
In SMC terms, you’ll know them as 
liquidity sweeps or liquidity grabs. 

81
00:07:20,000 --> 00:07:26,000
In price action terms, these are simply 
false breakouts or bull and bear traps,  

82
00:07:26,000 --> 00:07:31,280
where price pushes past key levels 
to trap traders on the wrong side.
  

83
00:07:31,920 --> 00:07:36,160
You'll spot these traps at 
key market highs and lows. 

84
00:07:36,160 --> 00:07:41,600
In an uptrend, price shoots below 
recent lows, triggering stop losses  

85
00:07:41,600 --> 00:07:48,640
and scaring traders out of good positions.
In downtrends, price spikes above recent  

86
00:07:48,640 --> 00:07:56,560
highs, trapping late buyers before dropping.
 
The mechanics work like this: Big players need  

87
00:07:56,560 --> 00:08:02,480
to find enough orders to fill their positions.
They push price into areas where they know  

88
00:08:02,480 --> 00:08:06,960
other traders place stops.
When these stops trigger,  

89
00:08:06,960 --> 00:08:14,160
they create instant buying or selling pressure 
that big players use to enter their positions.
  

90
00:08:14,160 --> 00:08:18,320
Smart money concepts simply 
added structure to this pattern. 

91
00:08:18,320 --> 00:08:24,000
They look for liquidity pools - areas 
with concentrated buy or sell orders. 

92
00:08:24,000 --> 00:08:28,720
These pools often sit just above 
resistance or below support,  

93
00:08:28,720 --> 00:08:35,920
where traders typically place their orders.
 
The validation process follows simple rules. 

94
00:08:35,920 --> 00:08:41,760
For a bull trap, price breaks above 
a recent high, then reverses sharply. 

95
00:08:41,760 --> 00:08:47,440
For a bear trap, price dips below 
a recent low before bouncing hard. 

96
00:08:47,440 --> 00:08:51,760
These moves happen fast, 
catching unprepared traders.
  

97
00:08:51,760 --> 00:08:56,880
You just need to understand how 
institutional traders use these sweeps. 

98
00:08:56,880 --> 00:09:03,840
In bullish markets, they need sell-side liquidity 
below lows, to fill their long positions 

99
00:09:03,840 --> 00:09:10,960
This fuels the next trend move up. They create 
these sweeps deliberately to find enough orders.
  

100
00:09:10,960 --> 00:09:18,080
During bearish swings, look for price to pull up 
to key levels. If no liquidity exists in previous  

101
00:09:18,080 --> 00:09:25,440
moves, smart money will create it through these 
sweeps. They build the trap before triggering it.
  

102
00:09:25,440 --> 00:09:32,160
So when trading bullish markets, it’s best 
to place buy orders after a bear trap. 

103
00:09:32,160 --> 00:09:36,480
You're buying into sell stops, 
just like big players do. 

104
00:09:36,480 --> 00:09:41,920
For bearish markets, you sell near 
recent highs after a bull trap.
  

105
00:09:41,920 --> 00:09:47,360
Whether you call this a false breakout 
or a liquidity sweep, this concept works  

106
00:09:47,360 --> 00:09:53,920
because it exploits basic trader psychology.
Most traders expect breakouts to continue. 

107
00:09:53,920 --> 00:10:00,160
When price reverses instead, it forces 
quick exits that fuel the new move. 

108
00:10:00,160 --> 00:10:05,920
Smart money concepts just explain the 
institutional side of this pattern.
  

109
00:10:05,920 --> 00:10:12,400
These sweeps often create decent reversals.
Once trapped traders realize their mistake,  

110
00:10:12,400 --> 00:10:17,600
they rush to exit.
This adds momentum to the new move. 
  

111
00:10:17,600 --> 00:10:22,720
The key lies in spotting potential 
sweep zones before they happen. 

112
00:10:22,720 --> 00:10:27,200
Look for areas where traders 
might cluster their stops. 

113
00:10:27,200 --> 00:10:31,680
Price tends to hunt these zones 
during major market turns. 

114
00:10:31,680 --> 00:10:36,040
The more obvious the level, the 
more likely it becomes a target.
  

115
00:10:36,040 --> 00:10:39,120
Mitigation
In Smart Money Concepts,  

116
00:10:39,120 --> 00:10:46,080
mitigation is just another name for what 
price traders call retests or pullbacks. 

117
00:10:46,080 --> 00:10:52,720
It’s the process of managing losses or offsetting 
unfavorable positions, when the market moves  

118
00:10:52,720 --> 00:10:59,920
against an institutional trader’s initial entry. 
 
Price action traders recognized this behavior but  

119
00:10:59,920 --> 00:11:07,120
didn’t give the institutional context behind it.
SMC just gave it a different name and explained  

120
00:11:07,120 --> 00:11:13,840
how big players adjust their strategies when the 
market doesn't go as they expected right away.
  

121
00:11:13,840 --> 00:11:19,680
To begin, let’s break down how 
mitigation works in the context of SMC. 

122
00:11:19,680 --> 00:11:25,520
Mitigation happens when the market retraces 
to a level where these institutions can reduce  

123
00:11:25,520 --> 00:11:32,560
or completely offset their losing positions.
For example, price might return to a specific  

124
00:11:32,560 --> 00:11:39,760
level, allowing them to close their earlier 
“buy” trades at breakeven or a smaller loss,  

125
00:11:39,760 --> 00:11:47,040
while simultaneously entering sell positions.
Essentially, mitigation allows them to transition  

126
00:11:47,040 --> 00:11:53,520
from a losing “buy” position into a profitable 
sell position, in the same price move.
  

127
00:11:54,160 --> 00:12:00,000
Price action traders have always tracked this 
behavior, though they described it differently. 

128
00:12:00,000 --> 00:12:06,160
They saw these retracements as pullbacks 
or retests of previous levels. 
  

129
00:12:06,160 --> 00:12:10,320
For example, if price broke 
below a key support level,  

130
00:12:10,320 --> 00:12:16,960
price action traders would look for the market to 
return to that level, before continuing downward. 

131
00:12:16,960 --> 00:12:22,960
They’d call this a "retest," where the 
broken support becomes new resistance. 

132
00:12:22,960 --> 00:12:28,320
SMC traders, on the other hand, would 
call this same movement "mitigation,"  

133
00:12:28,320 --> 00:12:33,920
especially if they believe it’s tied 
to institutions managing their risk.
  

134
00:12:33,920 --> 00:12:40,560
Mitigation often happens because institutions 
can’t execute their massive orders all at once. 

135
00:12:40,560 --> 00:12:45,520
Their volume is too large, and doing 
so would create too much slippage,  

136
00:12:45,520 --> 00:12:50,400
where the price moves unfavorably 
as their trades are filled. 

137
00:12:50,400 --> 00:12:54,480
Instead, they split their 
orders into smaller chunks. 

138
00:12:54,480 --> 00:13:01,280
This is why you often see price revisiting 
key levels before a strong continuation.
  

139
00:13:01,280 --> 00:13:07,360
Take this example: Suppose the market is 
in a downtrend, and price begins retracing  

140
00:13:07,360 --> 00:13:12,240
higher after a significant drop.
This retracement might test the  

141
00:13:12,240 --> 00:13:17,600
last bearish order block (the last up 
candle before the sharp move down). 

142
00:13:17,600 --> 00:13:23,360
Institutions that opened sell positions 
during the drop may have also opened temporary  

143
00:13:23,360 --> 00:13:29,360
buy positions to hedge against risk.
As price retraces to the order block,  

144
00:13:29,360 --> 00:13:36,880
they mitigate these temporary buy positions, 
closing them at breakeven or a small loss. 

145
00:13:36,880 --> 00:13:40,720
At the same time, they stack 
additional sell positions to  

146
00:13:40,720 --> 00:13:47,040
continue profiting from the downtrend.
 
Price action traders have always observed  

147
00:13:47,040 --> 00:13:53,280
this behavior, in the form of pullbacks 
to resistance levels or supply zones. 

148
00:13:53,280 --> 00:13:59,200
For them, these levels represent opportunities 
to trade in the direction of the trend after  

149
00:13:59,200 --> 00:14:04,560
a pause or minor correction. 
 
Mitigation isn’t random. It follows  

150
00:14:04,560 --> 00:14:11,280
predictable patterns tied to market structure.
In a bullish market, institutions may mitigate  

151
00:14:11,280 --> 00:14:17,360
their sell trades during retracements to 
key support levels. In a bearish market,  

152
00:14:17,360 --> 00:14:22,960
they may mitigate their buy trades during 
pullbacks to key resistance levels. 

153
00:14:22,960 --> 00:14:27,680
These levels often align with price 
action concepts like swing highs,  

154
00:14:27,680 --> 00:14:33,840
swing lows, or supply and demand zones.
The concept of mitigation or retest  

155
00:14:33,840 --> 00:14:38,960
offers a significant advantage. It 
explains why price often returns to  

156
00:14:38,960 --> 00:14:45,120
certain levels before continuing its trend. 
 
Let’s say you’re tracking a bearish trend,  

157
00:14:45,120 --> 00:14:51,680
and price breaks below a major support level.
Instead of chasing the breakdown, you wait for  

158
00:14:51,680 --> 00:14:57,360
price to retrace to the broken support.
This level now acts as resistance,  

159
00:14:57,360 --> 00:15:02,880
and the retracement offers an ideal 
entry point for a continuation trade. 

160
00:15:02,880 --> 00:15:08,800
SMC traders would call this mitigation, 
where institutions are offsetting their  

161
00:15:08,800 --> 00:15:14,800
earlier trades at the retest level.
 
Mitigation also highlights an important  

162
00:15:14,800 --> 00:15:20,640
truth: institutions aren’t perfect.
They don’t always get their entries right.  

163
00:15:20,640 --> 00:15:28,560
Just like retail traders, they deal with losses 
and use retracements to manage those losses. 

164
00:15:28,560 --> 00:15:34,320
This understanding helps to demystify 
the market. Smart money isn’t invincible. 

165
00:15:34,320 --> 00:15:39,680
They face the same challenges as everyone 
else, but they have the tools and strategies  

166
00:15:39,680 --> 00:15:44,960
to manage risk effectively. 
 
Mitigation can also explain why  

167
00:15:44,960 --> 00:15:51,360
some retracements go deeper than expected.
Institutions may need to push price slightly  

168
00:15:51,360 --> 00:15:57,200
beyond the obvious level to find enough 
liquidity to close their earlier trades. 

169
00:15:57,200 --> 00:16:02,720
For example, if price is retracing to 
a bearish order block, it might trade  

170
00:16:02,720 --> 00:16:09,040
slightly above the block, before reversing.
This deeper retracement occurs because the  

171
00:16:09,040 --> 00:16:15,280
institutions need to trigger more buy orders, more 
liquidity, to close their earlier sell positions. 

172
00:16:15,280 --> 00:16:22,240
Price action traders might call this a "deep 
pullback," while SMC traders see it as part of  

173
00:16:22,240 --> 00:16:24,480
the mitigation process.
 
Inducement 

174
00:16:24,480 --> 00:16:30,880
Inducement is a core principle in smart money 
concepts and is what price action traders  

175
00:16:30,880 --> 00:16:36,640
have long referred to as "trap setups."
It’s the market’s way of luring traders  

176
00:16:36,640 --> 00:16:43,760
into poor positions, by creating false moves 
that look convincing at first, but ultimately  

177
00:16:43,760 --> 00:16:49,920
work against those who fall for them. 
 
While the term “inducement” might sound  

178
00:16:49,920 --> 00:16:56,160
like a fresh idea, the behavior it describes 
has always been visible on price charts. 

179
00:16:56,160 --> 00:17:00,000
It’s just another way of understanding 
how the market manipulates  

180
00:17:00,000 --> 00:17:06,080
participants to generate liquidity.
 
As I said before, smart money don’t have  

181
00:17:06,080 --> 00:17:12,720
the luxury of entering and exiting trades like 
small traders. Their massive trade sizes require  

182
00:17:12,720 --> 00:17:19,440
liquidity, and they can’t execute their positions 
without triggering significant price movement. 

183
00:17:19,440 --> 00:17:25,040
Here’s where inducement comes into play. 
Institutions create false moves to attract  

184
00:17:25,040 --> 00:17:30,960
traders into the market, which generates the 
liquidity they need to fill their orders. 

185
00:17:31,520 --> 00:17:38,320
These false moves often appear as breakouts, 
double tops/bottoms, or other familiar patterns  

186
00:17:38,320 --> 00:17:45,520
that trap retail traders on the wrong side.
 
Take a simple example: price is trending upward  

187
00:17:45,520 --> 00:17:51,360
and forms a possible flag formation.
Retail traders see this resistance and  

188
00:17:51,360 --> 00:17:56,880
prepare to go long when price breaks 
it, expecting the market to continue. 

189
00:17:56,880 --> 00:18:03,440
Institutions, however, see this as an opportunity.
They drive price slightly above the resistance,  

190
00:18:03,440 --> 00:18:06,880
triggering stop loss orders 
from those who were short,  

191
00:18:06,880 --> 00:18:13,840
and enticing breakout buyers to enter the market.
After trapping these traders, the market reverses  

192
00:18:13,840 --> 00:18:20,640
sharply, leaving breakout buyers stuck in 
losing positions and forcing them to exit. 
  

193
00:18:20,640 --> 00:18:24,880
Inducement is often tied to 
the concept of liquidity pools. 

194
00:18:24,880 --> 00:18:31,360
These pools represent areas on the chart 
where stop losses or pending orders cluster. 

195
00:18:31,360 --> 00:18:37,120
For retail traders, these are the obvious 
levels, such as previous highs or lows,  

196
00:18:37,120 --> 00:18:44,400
equal tops of bottoms, or areas of consolidation.
Institutions target these zones, because they  

197
00:18:44,400 --> 00:18:50,480
know that triggering the orders in these areas 
will create liquidity to support their trades.
  

198
00:18:50,480 --> 00:18:56,400
Price action traders have always observed 
this behavior, describing it as stop  

199
00:18:56,400 --> 00:19:04,640
hunts or false breakouts. SMC gave it a new 
name—inducement—but the idea remains the same. 

200
00:19:04,640 --> 00:19:10,480
Consider double tops and double bottoms, 
which are classic price action patterns. 

201
00:19:10,480 --> 00:19:16,560
Retail traders often see these as reversal 
setups, expecting price to turn around when  

202
00:19:16,560 --> 00:19:20,720
it retests the same level. 
 
But institutions use these  

203
00:19:20,720 --> 00:19:24,800
patterns to their advantage.
They allow price to form what  

204
00:19:24,800 --> 00:19:32,000
looks like a double top or bottom, attracting 
traders who base their entries on these setups. 

205
00:19:32,000 --> 00:19:35,760
Then, they push price slightly 
beyond the level to trigger  

206
00:19:35,760 --> 00:19:42,880
stop losses, only to reverse shortly after.
This is why double tops and bottoms often fail  

207
00:19:42,880 --> 00:19:49,666
before eventually playing out—the initial move 
is an inducement designed to generate liquidity.
  

208
00:19:49,666 --> 00:19:52,480
Breaker blocks
Breaker blocks are just a refined version  

209
00:19:52,480 --> 00:19:58,640
of the price action concept of role reversal.
They highlight the same behavior of support  

210
00:19:58,640 --> 00:20:04,000
turning into resistance, or resistance 
turning into support, but with an added  

211
00:20:04,000 --> 00:20:10,800
focus on liquidity and institutional activity.
Price action traders have been using this  

212
00:20:10,800 --> 00:20:15,600
concept for years, even if they 
didn’t call it a breaker block.
  

213
00:20:15,600 --> 00:20:22,160
In SMC terms, a breaker block is basically 
a failed order block causing a shift in  

214
00:20:22,160 --> 00:20:28,240
market structure, and acting as a level 
of support or resistance for the price. 

215
00:20:28,240 --> 00:20:33,520
So, if price closes below the low of a 
bullish order block, you can mark that  

216
00:20:33,520 --> 00:20:40,720
failed order block as a bearish breaker block, 
which will now act as a resistance for price. 

217
00:20:40,720 --> 00:20:46,400
If price closes above the high of a bearish 
order block, you can mark that failed order  

218
00:20:46,400 --> 00:20:52,080
block as a bullish breaker block, which 
will now act as a support for price.
  

219
00:20:52,080 --> 00:20:57,840
Price action traders recognized this 
behavior early on and simply called  

220
00:20:57,840 --> 00:21:02,800
it "support turning into resistance" 
or "resistance turning into support." 

221
00:21:02,800 --> 00:21:06,800
This transition marks a shift 
in market sentiment. In price  

222
00:21:06,800 --> 00:21:13,120
action terms, this is called role reversal.
When price revisits these levels, it's often  

223
00:21:13,120 --> 00:21:20,160
a critical moment where big players show their 
hand, either defending or rejecting the level.
  

224
00:21:20,160 --> 00:21:26,640
You see these flips all the time: price is in 
an uptrend and hits a key resistance level. 

225
00:21:26,640 --> 00:21:32,080
Price consolidates below this level 
before making a strong breakout above it. 

226
00:21:32,080 --> 00:21:39,520
Later, when price retraces back to this breakout 
level, the old resistance now acts as support. 

227
00:21:39,520 --> 00:21:46,080
Price bounces off this level and continues upward.
Smart money traders would call this level  

228
00:21:46,080 --> 00:21:50,080
a bullish breaker block.
 
These zones often act as  

229
00:21:50,080 --> 00:21:56,480
magnets for price. Big players use them to 
manage their trades, either by mitigating  

230
00:21:56,480 --> 00:22:02,720
earlier positions or by entering new ones.
Whether you call it a breaker block or support  

231
00:22:02,720 --> 00:22:10,080
flip, the principle remains: these levels mark the 
battleground where institutions make their moves.
  

232
00:22:10,080 --> 00:22:16,320
Breaker blocks also tie into market structure.
They are most effective when aligned with the  

233
00:22:16,320 --> 00:22:18,880
overall trend.
For instance,  

234
00:22:18,880 --> 00:22:26,240
a bullish breaker block in an uptrend has a higher 
probability of holding, than one in a downtrend. 

235
00:22:26,240 --> 00:22:32,320
A bearish breaker block in a downtrend 
is more reliable than one in an uptrend. 

236
00:22:32,320 --> 00:22:39,200
Price action traders have always understood this, 
prioritizing retests that align with the trend.
 

237
00:22:39,760 --> 00:22:43,440
Fair Value Gaps
Fair value gaps are another example of how smart  

238
00:22:43,440 --> 00:22:50,240
money concepts are derived from price action.
In both cases, Fair Value Gaps point to  

239
00:22:50,240 --> 00:22:55,520
imbalances in the market, where supply 
and demand are not evenly matched,  

240
00:22:55,520 --> 00:23:01,280
leading to sharp, directional price moves.
Price action traders have long observed  

241
00:23:01,280 --> 00:23:06,320
these imbalances, describing 
them as gaps or inefficiencies,  

242
00:23:06,320 --> 00:23:13,040
left behind when price moves too quickly, to 
allow for balanced trading at certain levels. 

243
00:23:13,040 --> 00:23:20,560
SMC formalizes this observation, defining Fair 
Value Gaps within a clear three-candle sequence,  

244
00:23:20,560 --> 00:23:27,520
and connecting them to institutional activity.
 
In price action, a fair value gap is  

245
00:23:27,520 --> 00:23:35,200
identified as a strong imbalance between candles.
Specifically, it occurs when price moves sharply,  

246
00:23:35,200 --> 00:23:41,520
leaving a visible space on the chart – a gap 
– between the first and third candle’s wicks,  

247
00:23:41,520 --> 00:23:45,760
in a three-candle structure.
This gap signals that price  

248
00:23:45,760 --> 00:23:52,560
moved so decisively in one direction, that the 
opposing side of the trade couldn’t keep up. 

249
00:23:52,560 --> 00:24:00,000
This leads to a "void" or imbalance in the market, 
which price often revisits at a later time,  

250
00:24:00,000 --> 00:24:06,800
to "fill" as it seeks equilibrium.
 
Consider a bullish Fair Value Gap. 

251
00:24:06,800 --> 00:24:13,280
Price starts with a small bullish candle, the 
first candle in the sequence, then explodes upward  

252
00:24:13,280 --> 00:24:20,480
with a large bullish candle, the second candle.
Finally, a third candle follows, but its lower  

253
00:24:20,480 --> 00:24:26,800
wick doesn’t overlap with the upper wick of 
the first candle. This creates a gap between  

254
00:24:26,800 --> 00:24:33,040
the first and third candles, signaling that during 
the sharp upward move, there wasn’t enough selling  

255
00:24:33,040 --> 00:24:38,720
pressure to counterbalance the buying. 
 
Price action traders see this as an area  

256
00:24:38,720 --> 00:24:43,760
of imbalance, while SMC traders 
call it a fair value gap. 

257
00:24:43,760 --> 00:24:49,520
The idea is the same: this gap represents 
a level that price may return to,  

258
00:24:49,520 --> 00:24:55,600
either to fill the imbalance or to allow 
institutions to mitigate earlier positions.
  

259
00:24:55,600 --> 00:25:01,040
A bearish fair value gap works the 
same way but in the opposite direction. 

260
00:25:01,040 --> 00:25:07,760
This gap indicates a strong imbalance in favor 
of sellers, implying that price may revisit  

261
00:25:07,760 --> 00:25:15,440
this level in the future, to restore balance.
 
Fair value gaps often contain what SMC traders  

262
00:25:15,440 --> 00:25:20,000
call an "institutional candle", 
within the three-candle sequence. 

263
00:25:20,000 --> 00:25:26,320
In price action terms, these are simply strong 
momentum candles with above-average volume. 

264
00:25:26,320 --> 00:25:32,320
They represent areas where big players 
entered the market with significant orders,  

265
00:25:32,320 --> 00:25:39,840
pushing price sharply in one direction. 
 
For example, in a bullish gap, the large  

266
00:25:39,840 --> 00:25:44,960
bullish candle in the middle of the 
sequence is the institutional candle. 

267
00:25:44,960 --> 00:25:52,080
It’s the clearest evidence of aggressive buying 
by big players, which caused the sharp imbalance. 

268
00:25:52,080 --> 00:25:55,600
In a bearish gap, the large bearish candle in the  

269
00:25:55,600 --> 00:26:00,800
middle marks where institutions 
heavily sold, creating the gap.
  

270
00:26:00,800 --> 00:26:08,160
This institutional candle helps traders identify 
where smart money might re-engage with the market.  

271
00:26:08,160 --> 00:26:14,400
When price revisits the fair value gap, it 
often reacts near the institutional candle,  

272
00:26:14,400 --> 00:26:21,920
either reversing or continuing its previous trend.
Price action traders might describe this as  

273
00:26:21,920 --> 00:26:26,720
price revisiting a "key level" or 
a even a "demand or supply zone”. 

274
00:26:26,720 --> 00:26:33,120
When price returns to this zone, big players 
might step in again to defend their positions,  

275
00:26:33,120 --> 00:26:39,680
causing price to bounce and resume its trend. 
 
For price action traders, this is simply  

276
00:26:39,680 --> 00:26:45,360
a retracement to a support zone.
For SMC traders, it’s a revisit to  

277
00:26:45,360 --> 00:26:50,960
the fair value gap, where institutional 
activity is likely to take place. 

278
00:26:50,960 --> 00:26:55,600
This is why fair value gaps 
act as magnets for price. 

279
00:26:55,600 --> 00:27:02,240
Whether you call them fair value gaps or 
imbalances, the idea is the same: these gaps are  

280
00:27:02,240 --> 00:27:06,560
key zones where price is likely to return
 
ICT Power of 3 

281
00:27:06,560 --> 00:27:14,400
The “ICT Power of 3” is presented as a unique 
approach to decoding smart money manipulations. 

282
00:27:14,400 --> 00:27:20,800
It focuses on three distinct phases of 
price movement: Accumulation, Manipulation,  

283
00:27:20,800 --> 00:27:27,840
and Distribution. While the concept might seem 
innovative at first, it is actually a rebranding  

284
00:27:27,840 --> 00:27:34,480
of the well-established Wyckoff model. 
 
The phases of the “ICT Power of 3” align  

285
00:27:34,480 --> 00:27:40,160
almost perfectly with those outlined by 
Richard Wyckoff’s methodology, which has  

286
00:27:40,160 --> 00:27:47,600
been used to analyze market behavior for decades.
The first phase is the Accumulation. In the ICT  

287
00:27:47,600 --> 00:27:53,920
framework, this phase represents a period where 
smart money begin to build their positions,  

288
00:27:53,920 --> 00:27:59,520
without causing noticeable price movement.
Price action during this phase typically  

289
00:27:59,520 --> 00:28:06,400
consolidates, moving sideways in a range.
This behavior is no different from Wyckoff’s  

290
00:28:06,400 --> 00:28:13,120
accumulation phase, where large players 
quietly accumulate assets at lower prices,  

291
00:28:13,120 --> 00:28:18,480
in preparation for an upward move.
 
In the Wyckoff model, the accumulation  

292
00:28:18,480 --> 00:28:26,400
phase often includes a “spring,” a sharp downward 
move that breaks below the established range. 

293
00:28:26,400 --> 00:28:31,600
This move is designed to trigger stop 
losses from traders who are long,  

294
00:28:31,600 --> 00:28:38,160
and to encourage others to go short.
Once this liquidity is collected, price reverses  

295
00:28:38,160 --> 00:28:43,440
sharply and begins the mark-up phase.
In the “ICT Power of 3”,  

296
00:28:43,440 --> 00:28:50,480
this same behavior is labeled as Manipulation. 
 
The mark-up phase in Wyckoff’s model corresponds  

297
00:28:50,480 --> 00:28:57,200
to the Distribution phase in the “ICT Power 
of 3”. After institutions have completed their  

298
00:28:57,200 --> 00:29:04,160
accumulation and manipulated the market to collect 
liquidity, they begin to push price higher. 

299
00:29:04,160 --> 00:29:10,400
This is where the real trend unfolds, and price 
moves decisively in the intended direction. 

300
00:29:10,400 --> 00:29:15,040
Smart money uses this phase to 
offload their positions to latecomers,  

301
00:29:15,040 --> 00:29:19,360
who are now chasing the trend. 
 
In Wyckoff’s terms, this is the  

302
00:29:19,360 --> 00:29:25,360
"mark-up" period, where price climbs 
steadily as demand outweighs supply. 

303
00:29:25,360 --> 00:29:32,960
In ICT terminology, this is Distribution, where 
the positions accumulated earlier are sold off,  

304
00:29:32,960 --> 00:29:37,200
into the hands of retail traders 
who missed the initial move.
 
  

305
00:29:37,200 --> 00:29:43,280
So both the Wyckoff model and the “Power 
of 3” recognize that large players need  

306
00:29:43,280 --> 00:29:48,480
to manipulate price to generate the 
liquidity required for their trades. 

307
00:29:48,480 --> 00:29:54,720
Whether it’s labeled as a “spring,” “up thrust,” 
or “manipulation,” the goal is the same:  

308
00:29:54,720 --> 00:30:00,960
to trap traders and create the conditions 
necessary for a significant price move. 

309
00:30:00,960 --> 00:30:07,600
So no, the Power of 3 is not a groundbreaking 
revelation. It’s just a reinterpretation of the  

310
00:30:07,600 --> 00:30:11,680
Wyckoff model, rebranded with new terminology.
 
Price action vs SMC traders 

311
00:30:11,680 --> 00:30:17,920
Now, price action traders and SMC traders 
are often seen as two distinct groups with  

312
00:30:17,920 --> 00:30:23,200
different methods and perspectives.
This has led to many debates and  

313
00:30:23,200 --> 00:30:28,080
even a sense of rivalry between the two.
But when you strip away the terminology  

314
00:30:28,080 --> 00:30:33,120
and look at the core principles, it becomes 
clear that they’re trading the same thing.

